NFL Data Exploration¶

by Anthony Marcolongo¶

Investigation Overview¶

The goal of this presentation is to look at the various factors that affect NFL QB rating

Dataset Overview¶

I used the NFL QB career stats dataset for this project. This dataset contains passing stats for every player who has ever thrown a pass in an nfl game

# load in the dataset into a pandas dataframe
career_stats_qb = pd.read_csv('Career_Stats_Passing.csv');
In [3]:
career_stats_qb = career_stats_qb.drop(['Player Id', 'Position', 'Year', 'Team'], axis=1)
In [4]:
career_stats_qb = career_stats_qb.apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='ignore')
In [5]:
career_stats_qb['Ratings/game'] = career_stats_qb['Passer Rating']/career_stats_qb['Games Played']
In [6]:
career_stats_qb = career_stats_qb.dropna()
In [7]:
career_stats_qb = career_stats_qb.sort_values(by ='Ratings/game', ascending=False )
In [8]:
career_stats_qb.rename(columns = {'Passes Attempted':'Passes_Attempted', 'Games Played' : 'Games_Played', 'Passes Completed' : 'Passes_Completed', 'Completion Percentage' : 'Completion_Percentage', 'Pass Attempts Per Game' : 'Pass_Attempts_Per_Game', 'Passing Yards' : 'Passing_Yards', 'Passing Yards Per Attempt' : 'Passing_Yards_Per_Attempt', 'Passing Yards Per Game' : 'Passing_Yards_Per_Game', 'TD Passes' : 'TD_Passes', 'Percentage of TDs per Attempts' : 'Percentage_of_TDs_per_Attempts', 'Int Rate' : 'Int_Rate', 'Longest Pass' : 'Longest_Pass', 'Passes Longer than 20 Yards' : 'Passes_Longer_than_20_Yards', 'Passes Longer than 40 Yards' : 'Passes_Longer_than_40_Yards', 'Sacked Yards Lost' : 'Sacked_Yards_Lost', 'Passer Rating' : 'Passer_Rating'}, inplace = True)
In [9]:
career_stats_qb = career_stats_qb.replace({'--': 0}, regex=True)
In [10]:
career_stats_qb = career_stats_qb[career_stats_qb.loc[:]!=0].dropna()
In [11]:
career_stats_qb = career_stats_qb.apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='ignore')
In [12]:
career_stats_qb[['Passing_Yards', 'Longest_Pass']] = career_stats_qb[['Passing_Yards', 'Longest_Pass']].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce')
In [13]:
career_stats_qb_clean = career_stats_qb.query('Passes_Attempted > 100 and Games_Played > 10')
In [14]:
career_stats_qb_clean = career_stats_qb_clean.drop(['Passing_Yards'], axis = 1)
In [15]:
career_stats_qb_clean_new = career_stats_qb_clean.drop(['Name', 'Passes_Completed','Pass_Attempts_Per_Game', 'Passing_Yards_Per_Game', 'Percentage_of_TDs_per_Attempts', 'Int_Rate', 'Longest_Pass', 'Passes_Longer_than_20_Yards', 'Passes_Longer_than_40_Yards', 'Sacks', 'Sacked_Yards_Lost', 'Passer_Rating'], axis=1);
In [16]:
career_stats_qb_clean_new.corr();
In [17]:
# Create Ranking Based On Average Completion Rate
career_stats_qb_clean_new["Completion_Rank"] = np.where(career_stats_qb_clean_new.Completion_Percentage > career_stats_qb_clean_new.Completion_Percentage.mean(),
      "Above Average", "Below Average")

Ratings/game vs Passes Attempted¶

To get an idea of what a resonable cut off would be for passes attempted I will plot Ratings/game vs passes attempted

In [18]:
# Scatterplot -  Ratings/game vs Passes Attempted

plt.figure(figsize=[14.70, 8.27])
plt.scatter(career_stats_qb['Passes_Attempted'], career_stats_qb['Ratings/game']);
plt.xlabel("Passes Attempted")
plt.ylabel("QB Rating/Game");
plt.title("Passes Attempted Vs QB Rating".title(), fontsize = 14, weight = "bold" );

Scatterplots with Linear Regression lines¶

This is a series of graphs showing qb rating versus the following variables, games played, passes attempted, passing yards per attempt, TD passes, Ints. I included a linear regression line on each graph to give an idea of how well the graph fit the data.

In [23]:
# Scatterplots with Linear Regression lines
sb.pairplot(career_stats_qb_clean_new, y_vars = ['Ratings/game'], x_vars = ['Games_Played', 'Completion_Percentage', 'Passes_Attempted', 'Passing_Yards_Per_Attempt', 'TD_Passes', 'Ints'], kind="reg", height = 8.27,  aspect = 14.70/8.27);
plt.show();

Heatmap of all relevant variables¶

This is a heatmap showing how all of the variables in my dataset are correlated with each other. The numbers in each box represent the strength of the relation between the different variables, with 1 being the best match possible.
